Checking for appropriate priors

Jackson Zhou

Our task is to choose the distributions of \(\tilde{\theta}_1\) and \(\tilde{\theta}_2\) such that: \[ \alpha=\left(\frac{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}+1}\right)\left(\frac{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}+1}\right),\ \beta=\left(\frac{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}+1}\right)\left(\frac{1}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}+1}\right) \]

are distributed reasonably close to \(\text{Beta}(1.5,10)\) and \(\text{Beta}(10,1.5)\) respectively. To help us out, we first visualise samples from these Beta distributions using a histogram:

set.seed(3830)
ideal.alpha.sample <- rbeta(n = 10000, shape1 = 1.5, shape2 = 10)
ideal.beta.sample <- rbeta(n = 10000, shape1 = 10, shape2 = 1.5)

ideal.alpha.plot <- ideal.alpha.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Beta(1.5,10) samples",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
ideal.alpha.plot

ideal.beta.plot <- ideal.beta.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Beta(10,1.5) samples",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
ideal.beta.plot

I will now generate appropriate samples of \(\tilde{\theta}_1\) and \(\tilde{\theta}_2\) (with their distributions chosen via guess-and-check), and visualise the corresponding distributions of:

\[ A=\frac{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_1}+1},\ B=\frac{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}+1},\ C=\frac{1}{e^{\tilde{\theta}_2}+1},\ \alpha=A\cdot B\ \text{ and }\ \beta=A\cdot C \]

set.seed(3830)
theta.1.tilde.sample <- rnorm(n = 10000, mean = 8, sd = 1)
theta.2.tilde.sample <- rnorm(n = 10000, mean = -2, sd = 1)
A.sample <- exp(theta.1.tilde.sample)/(exp(theta.1.tilde.sample) + 1)
B.sample <- exp(theta.2.tilde.sample)/(exp(theta.2.tilde.sample) + 1)
C.sample <- 1/(exp(theta.2.tilde.sample) + 1)
alpha.sample <- A.sample*B.sample
beta.sample <- A.sample*C.sample

A.plot <- A.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of samples for A",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
A.plot

B.plot <- B.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of samples for B",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
B.plot

C.plot <- C.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of samples for C",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
C.plot

alpha.plot <- alpha.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of samples for alpha",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA, size = 1))
alpha.plot

beta.plot <- beta.sample %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = .)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour = "black", fill = "#888888") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of samples for beta",
       x = "Value",
       y = "Frequency") +
  ylim(c(0, 2000)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),

We see that by choosing the priors of \(\tilde{\theta}_1\) and \(\tilde{\theta}_2\) to be \(\mathcal{N}(8,1)\) and \(\mathcal{N}(-2,1)\) respectively, the corresponding distributions of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are reasonably close to the suggested priors. Checking that our samples of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) never sum to more than 1:

sum((alpha.sample + beta.sample) > 1)
## [1] 0

We see that none of the 10000 samples of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) generated using this method summed to more than 1, which is what we want. Making some grid plots for easier comparison:

plot_grid(ideal.alpha.plot, alpha.plot, nrow = 1)

plot_grid(ideal.beta.plot, beta.plot, nrow = 1)
